properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls will continue this afternoon. Additional snowfall accumulations of 5 cm are still expected this afternoon. The snow squalls will slowly shift south of the region by the early evening. The combination of strong and gusty winds reaching up to 60 km/h and heavy snow at times will result in a significant reduction in visibility in local blowing snow. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Snow squall warnings are issued when bands of snow form that produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall and wind is expected. Total snowfall: 15 to 30 cm. Maximum wind gusts: 80 km/h, with higher gusts likely over southeastern regions. Locations: eastern Newfoundland. Time span: Monday morning until early Tuesday morning. Remarks: A low pressure system tracking southeast of Newfoundland is forecast to bring significant amounts of snow to eastern parts of the province. Snow is expected to begin early Monday morning for southern portions of the island, and will begin mid-morning for more northern regions. There is potential for the snow to mix with or change over to rain or ice pellets over southern portions of the Avalon Monday afternoon. Strong northeasterly winds followed by strong northwesterlies are also expected Monday and Monday night. Maximum gusts are most likely going to range between 60 and 80 km/h for most areas. Along the south and east coasts, there is a possibility gusts could reach 100 km/h. These strong winds will combine with snow to reduce visibility in blowing snow. Conditions will improve on Tuesday morning. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Winter storm watches are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snow, snow squalls, and wind expected early this week. Total snowfall: 20 to 30 cm, with higher amounts likely over higher terrain. Maximum wind gusts: 80 km/h, with locally higher gusts possible. Locations: the west coast of Newfoundland from Port aux Basques to Parson's Pond. Time span: Monday evening through Tuesday. Remarks: Light snow is expected to spread across the west coast on Monday, but will become heavier Monday evening as onshore winds develop. This will generate onshore flurries and local snow squalls Monday night and Tuesday. Strong northwesterly winds are also expected Monday night and Tuesday. Maximum gusts are most likely going to range between 60 and 80 km/h for most areas. For the Port aux Basques area, there is a possibility gusts could reach 100 km/h. These strong winds will combine with snow to reduce visibility in blowing snow. Conditions will improve for most areas by the end of the day Tuesday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall expected Monday. Total snowfall: 10 to 15 cm. Maximum wind gusts: 60 to 80 km/h, with higher gusts possible over exposed coastal areas. Locations: central Newfoundland and western portions of the south coast. Time span: Monday morning through Monday night. Remarks: A low pressure system tracking southeast of Newfoundland is forecast to bring significant amounts of snow to parts of the province. Snow is expected to begin Monday morning for southern portions of the island, and will begin by mid-morning for more northern regions. Strong northeasterly winds followed by strong northwesterlies are also expected Monday and Monday night. Maximum gusts are most likely going to range between 60 and 80 km/h for most areas. These strong winds will combine with snow to reduce visibility in blowing snow. Conditions will improve for most areas on Tuesday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
